## 1. Clarify the constraints and target

First, let’s pin down what “usable without VRAM” means in engineering terms for this prototype.

You probably want something like:

- Host‑RAM only (or CPU + tiny GPU cache):  
  - All weights resident in system RAM.  
  - Optional: a small GPU (e.g. 4–8 GB) acting as an on‑demand cache for a few layers at a time.
- Quality target:  
  - Perplexity within ≈3–5% of the FP16/bfloat baseline on WikiText2 or an equivalent corpus. [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/yotta-labs_how-to-run-qwen36-35b-a3b-on-a-single-gpu-activity-7453419517604720640-INE_)
  - Subjective “vibes” (instruction‑following, reasoning) matching good Q4_K / AWQ baselines on the same model. [kaitchup.substack](https://kaitchup.substack.com/p/qwen35-quantization-similar-accuracy)
- Size target:  
  - 35B parameters, currently ~70 GB in FP16.  
  - With an effective average of ~3–4 bits/parameter you’re looking at ~13–18 GB raw weights, plus some metadata. [letsdatascience](https://letsdatascience.com/blog/llm-quantization-run-any-model-on-consumer-hardware)
  - That’s absolutely RAM‑friendly and only needs streaming to CPU caches, not VRAM.

Given how well Qwen3.5/3.6‑35B‑A3B already responds to strong 4‑bit schemes (AWQ, GPTQ, HQQ etc.), you’re starting from a model that demonstrably tolerates low‑bit compression with small perplexity hits. [reddit](https://www.reddit.com/r/LocalLLaMA/comments/1rfds1h/qwen3535ba3b_q4_quantization_comparison/)

