## 3. Prototype architecture: how to structure the method

Here’s an end‑to‑end prototype design that you can run layer‑wise on a single modest GPU with the rest on CPU, which is how most AWQ/GPTQ flows work today. [reddit](https://www.reddit.com/r/LocalLLaMA/comments/16brvb9/can_i_quantize_the_model_that_doesnt_fit_in_vram/)

### 3.1 Calibration and sensitivity analysis

1. **Calibration dataset:**
   - Grab ~2–10k sentences from a corpus that matches your deployment (e.g. WikiText, instruction logs, code mix, etc.). [newsletter.maartengrootendorst](https://newsletter.maartengrootendorst.com/p/a-visual-guide-to-quantization)
2. **Baseline forward pass:**
   - Run the FP16/bfloat model on this calibration set and store:
     - Per‑layer outputs.
     - Per‑token log‑probs and full‑sequence perplexity. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/html/2411.02530v1)
3. **Local sensitivity sweeps:**
   - For each module (e.g. layer L, weight matrix W):
     - Try a small grid of quantization configurations:
       - 3 vs 4 vs 6 bits.
       - Symmetric vs asymmetric.
       - Per‑tensor vs per‑channel vs per‑group scales.
       - With and without “salient weight” protection à la AWQ. [jarvislabs](https://jarvislabs.ai/blog/vllm-quantization-complete-guide-benchmarks)
     - Measure local increase in:
       - Reconstruction error (||W − Q(W)|| statistics).
       - Layer output error (||y_fp − y_q||).
       - Perplexity delta on calib set when *only that module* is quantized.

This gives you a table of “options” per module with (bits, size_savings, estimated_ppl_penalty). This is your error‑budget design space.

### 3.2 Global bit allocation (greedy knapsack)

Now cast it as an optimization:

- For each module m and configuration c:
  - Let \(\Delta S_{m,c}\) be size savings versus FP16.
  - Let \(\Delta P_{m,c}\) be perplexity increase.
- Budgets:
  - Total size ≤ target size S\_target.
  - Total perplexity ≤ P\_base × (1 + ε), with ε being say 0.03–0.05.

Prototype‑friendly approach:

- Start from all modules at a safe high‑bit configuration (e.g. 8‑bit per‑channel).
- Maintain a priority queue of candidate *downgrades* (e.g. 8b→4b, 4b→3b) sorted by \(\Delta S / \Delta P\) (bits saved per unit perplexity loss).
- Iteratively apply the best downgrade:
  - Update running size and PPL estimate.
  - Stop when:
    - Size target reached, or
    - Next step would exceed perplexity budget.

This gives you a *variable‑precision profile* for every matrix in the model.

You can make this fancier (e.g. small second‑order correction where multiple modules interact), but a greedy pass already gives you a solid novel method that’s easy to implement and publish.

