## 4. Representation & runtime for “no VRAM”

The second half of your “invention” is how you make this usable in practice on CPU‑only or tiny‑GPU systems.

### 4.1 Weight storage layout

- Store all weights in a custom packed format (e.g. a GGUF‑like container, or your own) with:
  - Bit‑width per tensor or per‑group.
  - Scale/zero‑point per tensor/group/channel as needed.
  - Flags for “high‑precision islands” (e.g. keep 1–2% of columns in FP16). [letsdatascience](https://letsdatascience.com/blog/llm-quantization-run-any-model-on-consumer-hardware)
- For CPU execution, you’ll want to:
  - Align groups to bytes/words for easy unpack.
  - Group channels into blocks that match your inner kernel width (e.g. 32, 64, 128 channels).

This is similar in spirit to how Q4\_K\_M and related schemes pack weights, but with per‑tensor variability and mixed high‑precision slices. [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/yotta-labs_how-to-run-qwen36-35b-a3b-on-a-single-gpu-activity-7453419517604720640-INE_)

### 4.2 Compute strategy (CPU + optional tiny GPU)

Usable without VRAM in practice looks like:

- **CPU‑only path:**
  - All weights in host RAM.
  - Quantized matrix × activation kernels using int8/int4/bit‑packed compute on CPU (SIMD).
  - KV cache also quantized (e.g. 4–6 bits) with dequantization on the fly. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/html/2411.02530v1)
- **Optional GPU assist:**
  - Keep 0–2 layers at a time in GPU VRAM (or even just activations).
  - Use pinned memory + async transfers to hide some latency.
  - GPU kernels can decode your variable‑bit weights, multiply with FP16 activations, and write back FP16 or FP8.

You do not need the entire 35B in VRAM; many practitioners already run 35B‑class Qwen 3.5/3.6 on a single 24 GB GPU with aggressive 4‑bit quantization and clever paging. Your method pushes that further by handling the full model in RAM and only ever streaming slices. [pub.towardsai](https://pub.towardsai.net/your-ai-agent-is-goldfish-brained-qwen3-6-35b-a3b-is-the-fix-b6a687c2094a)

