## 5. Specific technical choices for a first implementation

To make this concrete enough that you could code it in a long weekend:

### 5.1 Base quantizers

- For weights:
  - Use a GPTQ‑style solver for low‑bit per‑channel or per‑group quantization. [jarvislabs](https://jarvislabs.ai/blog/vllm-quantization-complete-guide-benchmarks)
  - Consider HQQ for faster, data‑free fallback on less sensitive modules. [letsdatascience](https://letsdatascience.com/blog/llm-quantization-run-any-model-on-consumer-hardware)
  - Always keep:
    - LayerNorm γ/β in FP16.
    - A small AWQ‑style “salient subset” of columns in FP16/FP8 for each linear that shows very high activation correlation with PPL. [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/yotta-labs_how-to-run-qwen36-35b-a3b-on-a-single-gpu-activity-7453419517604720640-INE_)
- For activations:
  - Start by leaving activations in FP16/FP32 to simplify.
  - Later, add 8‑bit or 4‑bit activation quantization on non‑critical paths; use straight‑through estimation or learned clipping if you go into QAT.

### 5.2 KV‑cache quantization

Memory footprint at long context is often dominated by KV cache, not just weights. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/html/2411.02530v1)

Prototype:

- Quantize K and V to 4–6 bits with per‑head or per‑group scales.
- Keep attention scores and softmax in FP16/FP32.
- Evaluate on long‑context perplexity or a synthetic recall benchmark to ensure no catastrophic degradation.

### 5.3 Fast profiling loop

Since you’re comfortable hacking infra:

- Build a small Python harness using:
  - vLLM or llama.cpp’s Python bindings as a starting point, or
  - Direct PyTorch model with custom quantization modules.
- Implement “quantize one module, run calibration, measure PPL.”
- Parallelize across modules with Ray / multiprocessing to speed up the sensitivity sweep.

Once you have the module‑wise error table, the global allocator is just a small knapsack‑like search over a few thousand decisions, which is trivial.

